<font color="#FF0000">WALL/RACISM</font><br>
<tt>Tue Feb 11 14:35:10 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
My thoughts as far as the Vietnam War Memorial being<br>
underground as it is described. I believe this has been <br>
well thought out. First of all, We always bury our dead, <br>
Those names on the wall are underground and I think their<br>
spirits are there behind the wall. It is a fitting tribute<br>
to all 58,000 plus that gave their lives for THAT country.<br>
    Next I would like to say, I have no idea why Maya lin<br>
would not want the American Flag flying over a memorial. <br>
This is the flag we fought for, like it or not. <br>
    Prejudice, I met a Vietnamese girl while I was in a <br>
PTSD Treatment Program, from the &quot;new generation&quot;, born<br>
after April 1975. She had never heard of a Afro American <br>
fighting in Vietnam. She stated there were no pictures<br>
of Afro Americans at the War Memorial in (Saigon), she<br>
calls it the other name in honor of Uncle Ho. I would <br>
way they are being well programmed to be Racism. No I am<br>
not an Afro American, I am Caucasion, it does disturb me <br>
that Credit isn't given where credit is due. <br>
     I was in country 1967-68 with the 1st Marine Div.<br>
and then the 3rd Marine Div. in Tank Bns. <br>
     I just want to make the point that everyone that fought<br>
there should get the credit, the American Flag should fly,<br>
and lastly I think it is a fitting tribute to the names at<br>
The Wall to have it in a depression so their spirits have<br>
a fitting place to be.
